SIMPLE: inanition
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Inanition
<hw>In`a*ni"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>inanition</ets>, L. <ets>inanitio</ets> emptiness, fr.
<ets>inanire</ets> to empty, fr. <ets>inanis</ets> empty. Cf.
<er>Inane</er>.]</ety> <def>The condition of being inane; emptiness;
lack of fullness, as in the vessels of the body; hence, specifically,
exhaustion from lack of food, either from partial or complete
starvation, or from a disorder of the digestive apparatus, producing the
same result.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Feeble from <qex>inanition</qex>, inert from weariness.</q>
<rj><qau>Landor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Repletion and <qex>inanition</qex> may both do harm in two
contrary extremes.</q> <rj><qau>Burton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inanity</ent>⟦br⟧
